    <h1>How the world&#x2019;s first FLNG ves&#xAD;sel con&#xAD;ver&#xAD;sion was done</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201110/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-10"><time>2020-11-10</time></a>
        - <span>BUSINESS</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Kep­pel Corp’s rig-build­ing unit Kep­pel Off­shore & Marine (Kep­pel O&M) is cur­rently work­ing on its sec­ond FLNG con­ver­sion, hav­ing com­pleted the world’s first con­verted float­ing liq­ue­fac­tion ves­sel (FLNG) three years ago. Con­vert­ing liq­ue­fied nat­u­ral gas car­ri­ers to FLNGs is one way in which Kep­pel O&M has sought to help cus­tomers re­duce their car­bon emis­sions, which more firms are com­mit­ting to do. Choo Yun Ting takes a look at how Kep­pel O&M con­verted the world’s first FLNG ves­sel, Hilli Episeyo.</p>

